Joseph R. Biden Jr., commonly known as Joe Biden, is an American politician who served as the 46th President of the United States from January 2021. He previously served as the Vice President under President Barack Obama from 2009 to 2017. Biden has had a long and distinguished political career, spanning over four decades. He also served as a U.S. Senator from Delaware from 1973 to 2009.

During his time as President, Biden has focused on addressing various pressing issues, including the COVID-19 pandemic, racial inequality, climate change, and economic recovery. He has taken significant steps to combat the pandemic, such as implementing a national vaccination campaign and providing economic relief to individuals and businesses affected by the crisis. Biden has also made efforts to address racial injustice by promoting police reform and advocating for voting rights.

In terms of foreign policy, Biden has aimed to repair relationships with international allies and reengage with global organizations. He has taken steps to rejoin the Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization, among other international agreements and organizations. Additionally, Biden has focused on addressing the threat of climate change by implementing various environmental policies and goals.

Overall, Joseph R. Biden Jr. has been dedicated to tackling key issues both domestically and internationally during his presidency. His leadership and policy initiatives aim to address the challenges facing the United States and work towards a more inclusive and sustainable future.